    {
      "id": "38d2cc446e100526920b04e514c873e746e92a98",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 805,
        "name": "Neil Brown",
        "email": "neil@brown.name",
        "username": "neilbrown"
      },
      "date": "2019-11-05 21:28:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nJust checking - you do know that in recent kernels, %p doesn't report the actual address, but rather a hash of the address.  So you can know if two addresses are the same, but you cannot use the address to help examine a crashdump.\nGiven that - are you still happy with %p ??\n%px will print the actual address, but it is descouraged as it can be used to defeat address-space-randomization.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "1b30299442183c235ec4c9e6230c881cd3ee2329",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2019-11-05 21:30:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\n> Just checking - you do know that in recent kernels, %p doesn't\n > report the actual address, but rather a hash of the address.  So\n > you can know if two addresses are the same, but you cannot use the\n > address to help examine a crashdump.\n > Given that - are you still happy with %p ??\n > %px will print the actual address, but it is descouraged as it can\n > be used to defeat address-space-randomization.\n\nWell, shit. I did not know that.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "de9109c2b83cf9b9cb3f38dc79135beb0f37ff45",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 805,
        "name": "Neil Brown",
        "email": "neil@brown.name",
        "username": "neilbrown"
      },
      "date": "2019-11-05 21:42:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nThe hashing landed in 4.15, so rhel8 and ubuntu18 should have it.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "e183e9404b7ccfcc1aad49e10e65c8e3c03d2a6c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2019-11-05 21:43:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1\n\nThanks for the heads up, Neil.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "2084aaf4e0da09665c02a3df4886970956bbf482",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 808,
        "name": "Shaun Tancheff",
        "email": "shaun.tancheff@hpe.com",
        "username": "stancheff"
      },
      "date": "2020-02-13 02:14:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nBased on some chatting in slack you may want to change %p to %px or %pK\n%px -> print the address (not a hash)\n%pK -> print the address conditionally per /proc/sys/kernel/kptr_restrict sysctl\n\nhttps://lwn.net/Articles/420403/\n\nAnd to clarify a little more I did a quick test on Ubuntu 5.3 kernel:\n/proc/sys/kernel/kptr_restrict set to 1:\nFeb 12 20:09:34 wandering kernel: [1221025.968970] %p => 00000000ca86de39\nFeb 12 20:09:34 wandering kernel: [1221025.968971] %pK => ffffb755851c3c57\nFeb 12 20:09:34 wandering kernel: [1221025.968972] %px => ffffb755851c3c57\n\n/proc/sys/kernel/kptr_restrict set to 0:\nFeb 12 20:10:36 wandering kernel: [1221088.195319] %p => 00000000c2fe1af4\nFeb 12 20:10:36 wandering kernel: [1221088.195320] %pK => 00000000c2fe1af4\nFeb 12 20:10:36 wandering kernel: [1221088.195320] %px => ffffb755827cbc57\n\n/proc/sys/kernel/kptr_restrict set to 2:\nFeb 12 20:11:01 wandering kernel: [1221112.679491] %p => 00000000b69e927b\nFeb 12 20:11:01 wandering kernel: [1221112.679491] %pK => 0000000000000000\nFeb 12 20:11:01 wandering kernel: [1221112.679492] %px => ffffb7558084bc57",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    }
  ],
  "current_revision_number": 6,
